# Basic use

To create a shape, simply create its instance and position it.

```javascript
const triangle = new Triangle({
  type: "right",
  a: 100,
  b: 100,
  orientation: "topRight",
  style: {
    fill: "#9b59b6",
    stroke: "#8e44ad",
    strokeWidth: 3,
  },
});

triangle.position({
  relativeFrom: leftTriangle.center,
  relativeTo: artboard.contentBox.center,
  x: -250,
  y: 0,
  boxReference: "contentBox",
});
```

# Positioning of geometrical shapes

Normal, non-geometry content is positioned by nesting Containers that have direction. The best way to create complicated geometry is to create Container with "direction: 'freeform'" and auto width and height, and add an object to the center of it, and later position all objects relatively to our new object.

```javascript
const centerCircle = new Circle({
  radius: 60,
  style: {
    fill: "#e74c3c",
    stroke: "#c0392b",
    strokeWidth: 3,
  },
});

centerCircle.position({
  relativeFrom: centerCircle.center,
  relativeTo: container.contentBox.center,
  x: 0,
  y: 0,
  boxReference: "contentBox",
});

container.addElement(centerCircle);
```

This way, we don't need to worry about what happens to the container - it's automatically sized.

# Adjacence

You can intuitively move things along lines and in relation to points without doing complex computation. This is the mandated way of creating things with w2l.

Below, a way of constructing a Pythagorean theorem visualisation without calculating position of any of the object - this way, you know that the squares have adjacent sides with triangle.

```javvascript
// Create a 3-4-5 right triangle (classic Pythagorean triple)
const triangle = new Triangle({
  type: "right",
  a: 120, // Base = 3 units
  b: 90, // Height = 4 units
  // Hypotenuse will be 5 units (150px)
  orientation: "bottomLeft",
  style: {
    fill: "#34495e",
    stroke: "#ecf0f1",
    strokeWidth: 3,
  },
});

triangle.position({
  relativeFrom: triangle.center,
  relativeTo: container.contentBox.center,
  x: 0,
  y: 0,
  boxReference: "contentBox",
});

container.addElement(triangle);

// Get the three sides
const sides = triangle.sides;
const colors = ["#e74c3c", "#3498db", "#2ecc71"]; // Red, Blue, Green

// Place a square on each side
const squares = [];
sides.forEach((side, index) => {
  const square = new Rect({
    width: side.length,
    height: side.length,
    style: {
      fill: colors[index],
      fillOpacity: 0.7,
      stroke: colors[index],
      strokeWidth: 2,
    },
  });

  // Position square at the center of the side
  square.position({
    relativeFrom: square.center,
    relativeTo: side.center,
    x: 0,
    y: 0,
    boxReference: "contentBox",
  });

  // Rotate to align with the side
  square.rotate(side.angle);

  // Move it outward along the normal
  square.translate(side.outwardNormal, side.length / 2);

  // Add square to container
  container.addElement(square);
  squares.push(square);
});
```

If you would like to identify which side of the .sides is adjacent, you can figure it out simply by knowing they're always drawn counter-clockwise.

Drawing something next to it is also relatively trivial as we can use our side.center, etc.. positioning accessors.

# Marking angles, altitudes

All geometrical figures expose methods that allow for annotating them with mathematical information such as angles, etc.

```javascript
square.showAngles({
  rightAngleMarker: "square",
});
```

Use those methods over any other approach.

# Labels

Each of the figures exposes an auto-labelling method. If you need them for a mathematical context, use it.
